=== Allergic Responses
<sec:allergic-responses>

==== Food Sensitivities

Many ME/CFS patients report food intolerances:

    - May be IgE-mediated (true allergy) or non-IgE-mediated
    - Common triggers: gluten, dairy, histamine-rich foods
    - Mechanism may involve mast cell activation or gut barrier dysfunction
    - Elimination diets help some patients

==== Environmental Allergies

Increased sensitivity to environmental factors is reported in ME/CFS:

    - Pollen, dust mites, mold
    - Chemical sensitivities (fragrances, cleaning products)
    - Medication sensitivities
    - May reflect mast cell hyperreactivity or neurogenic inflammation

==== Shared Immune Pathways

Links between allergy and ME/CFS:

    - Th2 skewing in some patients @skowera2004type2
    - Mast cell dysfunction
    - Neurogenic inflammation (sensory nerve-mast cell interactions)

Note an important qualification regarding IgE. Although a Th2 cytokine bias is documented in ME/CFS @skowera2004type2, this is *not* accompanied by elevated immunoglobulin E: two independent case-control studies found total IgE (normal once stratified by atopic status) @reparramirez2001igelevels and allergen-specific IgE @kowal2002prevalence to be normal in ME/CFS. Any allergic-type mechanism in ME/CFS therefore appears to operate through IgE-independent (non-IgE mast cell) pathways rather than classical IgE-mediated allergy. At the population level, infection itself does raise the incidence of new allergic disease @oh2024incident, but this is a general post-infectious phenomenon rather than evidence of an IgE-driven ME/CFS state. The antigen-specific IgE hypothesis (to spike or tick antigens) and its counterarguments are examined in @sec:ige-antigen-sensitization.

